WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.060 --> 00:00:05.650
NILOFER MERCHANT: Today, any
individual has access to

00:00:05.650 --> 00:00:08.750
information that 20 years ago,
only the richest billionaire

00:00:08.750 --> 00:00:10.880
had access to.

00:00:10.880 --> 00:00:13.930
Seems kind of obvious, right,
to this audience of people?

00:00:13.930 --> 00:00:16.990
And yet, the implications for
business, and business models,

00:00:16.990 --> 00:00:19.320
and what creates power in those
business models, it

00:00:19.320 --> 00:00:21.560
changes everything.

00:00:21.560 --> 00:00:23.520
So I wanted to spend a little
bit of time talking about the

00:00:23.520 --> 00:00:26.110
business models, what changes,
what it means for us as

00:00:26.110 --> 00:00:29.200
leaders, and what I think people
can do, especially some

00:00:29.200 --> 00:00:31.200
of you who might be going out
and maybe starting your own

00:00:31.200 --> 00:00:34.340
companies post Google, what I
think that means for you as

00:00:34.340 --> 00:00:35.990
entrepreneurs.

00:00:35.990 --> 00:00:37.750
So the gorillas of the
marketplace, the way

00:00:37.750 --> 00:00:40.460
organizations had power, here
are some of the constructs

00:00:40.460 --> 00:00:41.560
that they considered.

00:00:41.560 --> 00:00:46.520
One was that being bigger than
everyone else meant that they

00:00:46.520 --> 00:00:49.060
could have pricing power in the
marketplace, meant that

00:00:49.060 --> 00:00:53.040
they could control which
suppliers they had access to.

00:00:53.040 --> 00:00:55.410
It meant that they had this
thing called sustainable

00:00:55.410 --> 00:00:57.790
competitive advantage.

00:00:57.790 --> 00:00:59.400
Sustainable competitive
advantage has now

00:00:59.400 --> 00:01:01.190
gone from 40 years--

00:01:01.190 --> 00:01:02.310
long arcs--

00:01:02.310 --> 00:01:05.940
to 12 years in old industries,
and 5 in fast moving

00:01:05.940 --> 00:01:06.590
industries.

00:01:06.590 --> 00:01:08.370
So it's really hard to use
that term, sustainable

00:01:08.370 --> 00:01:10.350
competitive advantage, anymore
because it doesn't mean the

00:01:10.350 --> 00:01:11.480
same thing.

00:01:11.480 --> 00:01:14.140
Any advantage that an old
organization had when they

00:01:14.140 --> 00:01:16.900
tried to build up a moat around
their business actually

00:01:16.900 --> 00:01:18.660
doesn't hold true.

00:01:18.660 --> 00:01:21.410
And in fact, the first chapter
of "Social Era" starts with an

00:01:21.410 --> 00:01:25.450
obituary to this character,
traditional strategy.

00:01:25.450 --> 00:01:28.310
And I, basically, say it was
good while we had you.

00:01:28.310 --> 00:01:29.530
You had a good life.

00:01:29.530 --> 00:01:31.000
But you're dead now.

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:34.220
And we ought to honor the
rules of a new era.

00:01:34.220 --> 00:01:37.860
But gorillas, these big
organizations, are actually

00:01:37.860 --> 00:01:40.340
facing all the changes in the
marketplace, whether it was

00:01:40.340 --> 00:01:43.180
crowd sourcing, or SaaS plays,
or the things that

00:01:43.180 --> 00:01:45.920
fundamentally lowered the cost
structure of having an

00:01:45.920 --> 00:01:46.920
organization.

00:01:46.920 --> 00:01:50.200
And they're looking at it and
thinking to themselves, all

00:01:50.200 --> 00:01:53.390
this is really causing me to
have to compete against a much

00:01:53.390 --> 00:01:54.710
leaner organization.

00:01:54.710 --> 00:01:57.130
And so it's almost like they sit
there and they think, how

00:01:57.130 --> 00:01:59.250
do I go on a diet?

00:01:59.250 --> 00:02:01.510
But they're missing the
fundamental construct that

00:02:01.510 --> 00:02:03.940
something so big and
shifted that it's

00:02:03.940 --> 00:02:07.700
not just about Spandex--

00:02:07.700 --> 00:02:10.889
sorry for such a girl
reference there.

00:02:10.889 --> 00:02:12.650
Women wear these things
called Spanx.

00:02:12.650 --> 00:02:14.900
Any of you have ever
heard of Spanx?

00:02:14.900 --> 00:02:16.000
Men also have them.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:17.360
But I'd be really scared if one
of you guys admitted that

00:02:17.360 --> 00:02:19.960
you wore Spanx.

00:02:19.960 --> 00:02:22.570
Apparently Roger Moore in the
James Bond movies, because he

00:02:22.570 --> 00:02:25.030
wasn't in good shape,
actually wore Spanx.

00:02:25.030 --> 00:02:26.670
That was the early generation
of Spanx.

00:02:26.670 --> 00:02:28.800
There you go.

00:02:28.800 --> 00:02:30.210
Trivia.

00:02:30.210 --> 00:02:32.170
So big organizations are
often thinking--

00:02:32.170 --> 00:02:34.290
seeing all these things and
seeing that they're performing

00:02:34.290 --> 00:02:36.840
against these lighter based
companies-- and thinking, I've

00:02:36.840 --> 00:02:40.110
just got to figure out how
to do more with less.

00:02:40.110 --> 00:02:42.650
And I think that's actually
a false architecture.

00:02:42.650 --> 00:02:45.190
Instead I think there's
something

00:02:45.190 --> 00:02:46.790
entirely new coming on.

00:02:46.790 --> 00:02:49.610
And I call that thing
the social era.

00:02:49.610 --> 00:02:52.490
And as I talk about social, most
people finish the word

00:02:52.490 --> 00:02:54.830
social with the word media.

00:02:54.830 --> 00:02:57.760
So I just want to slow down and
say, for me, social is not

00:02:57.760 --> 00:02:58.080
about media.

00:02:58.080 --> 00:03:00.390
It's not a marketing or
communications thing.

00:03:00.390 --> 00:03:02.000
And in fact, it might just be
helpful to kind of make some

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:05.520
distinctions about other key
terms that people have used.

00:03:05.520 --> 00:03:09.600
So social media, obviously,
was created around the

00:03:09.600 --> 00:03:11.130
Cluetrain Manifesto.

00:03:11.130 --> 00:03:12.630
It's done a great thing
in the world.

00:03:12.630 --> 00:03:17.320
It's like the Red Bull
of organizations.

00:03:17.320 --> 00:03:20.340
Makes you maybe go faster,
accelerate communications, and

00:03:20.340 --> 00:03:21.200
the speed of communications.

00:03:21.200 --> 00:03:22.480
So it is like Red Bull
in that way.

00:03:22.480 --> 00:03:26.000
But it's still just about
communications and creating a

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:27.860
dialogue versus a monologue.

00:03:27.860 --> 00:03:28.670
Enterprise 2.0.

00:03:28.670 --> 00:03:30.950
How many of you guys have
heard that term?

00:03:30.950 --> 00:03:32.530
Oh, not so much this group.

00:03:32.530 --> 00:03:35.190
So Enterprise 2.0 was coined
by Andrew McAfee

00:03:35.190 --> 00:03:36.500
about six years ago.

00:03:36.500 --> 00:03:38.790
And the idea was that the
tools would allow

00:03:38.790 --> 00:03:41.360
organizations to function
differently.

00:03:41.360 --> 00:03:43.430
Peter Kim actually came up
with this idea of social

00:03:43.430 --> 00:03:45.040
business and actually kind
of stole the term

00:03:45.040 --> 00:03:46.130
from Muhammad Yunus.

00:03:46.130 --> 00:03:48.700
Muhammad Yunus said, social
business we can actually care

00:03:48.700 --> 00:03:50.600
about meaning and work.

00:03:50.600 --> 00:03:53.330
And Peter Kim came along and
said-- and he was working at

00:03:53.330 --> 00:03:55.430
Dachis Group at the time, which
is a marketing agency--

00:03:55.430 --> 00:03:56.730
said, you know what?

00:03:56.730 --> 00:03:59.370
What if we could actually use
these tools to actually create

00:03:59.370 --> 00:04:02.530
wealth and exchange across all
the players, so not just

00:04:02.530 --> 00:04:05.230
shareholders but customers,
community.

00:04:05.230 --> 00:04:06.450
So thinking about it that way.

00:04:06.450 --> 00:04:08.590
But he fundamentally didn't
challenge whether or not an

00:04:08.590 --> 00:04:11.340
organization was still needed.

00:04:11.340 --> 00:04:13.730
And so in "Social Era," I'm
basically saying two things.

00:04:17.180 --> 00:04:22.330
One is, just as a comparison
point, in the industrial era

00:04:22.330 --> 00:04:26.570
when oil, and capital,
land, limited

00:04:26.570 --> 00:04:29.190
resources were at play.

00:04:29.190 --> 00:04:31.150
Then what you needed was
an organization that

00:04:31.150 --> 00:04:32.540
could create scale.

00:04:32.540 --> 00:04:35.240
And value was fundamentally
about what an organization

00:04:35.240 --> 00:04:37.360
could do and you had to belong
within the walls of that

00:04:37.360 --> 00:04:39.060
organization to create value.

00:04:39.060 --> 00:04:41.190
"Social Era," it's exactly
the opposite.

00:04:41.190 --> 00:04:45.040
It starts with a single,
connected human.

00:04:45.040 --> 00:04:47.805
Whether or not you belong to an
organization, or work for

00:04:47.805 --> 00:04:52.550
an organization, pretty much
a secondary effect.

00:04:52.550 --> 00:04:56.330
And so what that changes is
why are we all together?

00:04:56.330 --> 00:04:58.410
And if there's all those people
out there who could be

00:04:58.410 --> 00:05:00.410
creating value with us,
how do we engage that?

00:05:00.410 --> 00:05:02.080
So that's the institutional
view.

00:05:02.080 --> 00:05:05.360
And then, at an individual
level, it changes because we

00:05:05.360 --> 00:05:08.910
get to start thinking about
ourselves not just am I an

00:05:08.910 --> 00:05:11.140
employee of such and such?

00:05:11.140 --> 00:05:14.800
But what is this unit of value
creation that I bring?

00:05:14.800 --> 00:05:17.030
And where do I want to
plug that unit--

00:05:17.030 --> 00:05:18.550
such a mechanical term--

00:05:18.550 --> 00:05:19.920
into?

00:05:19.920 --> 00:05:22.020
If I'm a LEGO block, what other
LEGO blocks do I want to

00:05:22.020 --> 00:05:24.670
go join with so I can
start creating value

00:05:24.670 --> 00:05:27.470
and build from there?

00:05:27.470 --> 00:05:31.220
The shift changes how we think
about leadership, how we think

00:05:31.220 --> 00:05:34.690
about business models, how we
think about even just when we

00:05:34.690 --> 00:05:35.980
think about scaling.

00:05:35.980 --> 00:05:37.230
What is scaling?

00:05:38.980 --> 00:05:40.490
So I'll give you a couple
examples of how

00:05:40.490 --> 00:05:41.690
that comes to play.

00:05:41.690 --> 00:05:43.460
Singularity University, how
many of you guys know

00:05:43.460 --> 00:05:45.720
Singularity because it's
here in the Valley?

00:05:45.720 --> 00:05:45.980
There you go.

00:05:45.980 --> 00:05:48.320
Big group.

00:05:48.320 --> 00:05:50.310
Aimed at people who have
already gotten graduate

00:05:50.310 --> 00:05:53.650
degrees but who fundamentally
want to change the world.

00:05:53.650 --> 00:05:56.550
And their idea was instead
of teaching people

00:05:56.550 --> 00:05:58.630
backward-looking information,
let's teach them

00:05:58.630 --> 00:06:00.430
forward-looking information
because if they're going to be

00:06:00.430 --> 00:06:03.900
true change agents in the
world, they need that.

00:06:03.900 --> 00:06:06.350
But that changes really often.

00:06:06.350 --> 00:06:09.630
What is new and current three
years ago is not as new and

00:06:09.630 --> 00:06:10.950
current today.

00:06:10.950 --> 00:06:13.080
And so you have to build an
organizational construct that

00:06:13.080 --> 00:06:15.580
is fundamentally designed for
speed for that kind of

00:06:15.580 --> 00:06:17.050
flexibility.

00:06:17.050 --> 00:06:21.190
So they deliver almost 400 hours
of curriculum with seven

00:06:21.190 --> 00:06:23.240
full-time staff.

00:06:23.240 --> 00:06:26.010
That seven full-time staff
basically hold the mission of

00:06:26.010 --> 00:06:27.350
the organization.

00:06:27.350 --> 00:06:30.510
And then they recruit
the next group.

00:06:30.510 --> 00:06:33.470
The next group, that sort of
10 thought leaders across

00:06:33.470 --> 00:06:36.630
robotics, and biomedical stuff,
and so on, tissue

00:06:36.630 --> 00:06:41.120
engineering, really innovative
stuff, that 10 people then go

00:06:41.120 --> 00:06:43.840
find the next 20 people who are
the leaders in the field.

00:06:43.840 --> 00:06:45.690
20 people can happen
from anywhere.

00:06:45.690 --> 00:06:48.710
So inherently global, inherently
social, using

00:06:48.710 --> 00:06:50.930
collaborative technologies to
bring them all together.

00:06:50.930 --> 00:06:53.220
No one needs to be in one
particular place.

00:06:53.220 --> 00:06:54.440
They come in.

00:06:54.440 --> 00:06:56.060
They deliver their
piece of value.

00:06:56.060 --> 00:06:57.200
They leave again.

00:06:57.200 --> 00:07:00.670
At the end of every semester,
it collapses all back down.

00:07:00.670 --> 00:07:03.570
So you sit there, and you go,
what do we need to actually

00:07:03.570 --> 00:07:05.210
deliver next semester?

00:07:05.210 --> 00:07:08.390
Change is built into the
organizational design.

00:07:08.390 --> 00:07:10.680
Change is built into how they
even think about things.

00:07:10.680 --> 00:07:14.400
So it's not how do we protect
and maintain tenured staff, or

00:07:14.400 --> 00:07:15.890
these buildings, right?

00:07:15.890 --> 00:07:19.110
But what is it we really want
to be called to do?

00:07:19.110 --> 00:07:21.960
And then what is the way in
which we'll modularly figure

00:07:21.960 --> 00:07:24.250
out who needs to belong
as part of our tribe?

00:07:24.250 --> 00:07:26.610
Those people certainly are
affiliated with Singularity

00:07:26.610 --> 00:07:29.020
University in the sense that
some of the best leaders in

00:07:29.020 --> 00:07:31.070
the world come and
teach there.

00:07:31.070 --> 00:07:33.540
They don't work for
that institution.

00:07:33.540 --> 00:07:35.960
And the institution gets to get
value from that exchange.

00:07:39.520 --> 00:07:40.440
TED.

00:07:40.440 --> 00:07:42.790
Probably everyone in this group
has watched a TED video.

00:07:42.790 --> 00:07:44.700
Yes?

00:07:44.700 --> 00:07:48.770
So TED actually started out as
a really elite conference--

00:07:48.770 --> 00:07:50.790
originally one, now two--

00:07:50.790 --> 00:07:52.640
where just a couple, maybe
like 1,000, people

00:07:52.640 --> 00:07:54.320
participated.

00:07:54.320 --> 00:07:58.035
And as those people came
together, they would come and

00:07:58.035 --> 00:07:58.960
they'd be influential
and stuff.

00:07:58.960 --> 00:08:00.110
But then they'd leave.

00:08:00.110 --> 00:08:01.970
And four years ago or so they
said, you know, maybe we

00:08:01.970 --> 00:08:04.220
should share the talks
that are happening.

00:08:04.220 --> 00:08:05.750
We should share them online.

00:08:05.750 --> 00:08:08.130
So they started doing something
with YouTube to

00:08:08.130 --> 00:08:10.580
share videos as they were
being created by the

00:08:10.580 --> 00:08:13.530
conference, which upped the
production level and focused

00:08:13.530 --> 00:08:14.280
all that, which is good.

00:08:14.280 --> 00:08:16.030
Sharing free, good.

00:08:16.030 --> 00:08:19.170
But the thing that really made
TED more powerful is they

00:08:19.170 --> 00:08:21.280
figured out there were actually
some people that

00:08:21.280 --> 00:08:23.440
might want to create TED
conferences, too.

00:08:23.440 --> 00:08:24.490
TEDxes.

00:08:24.490 --> 00:08:26.480
And so they created this
little sub-brand.

00:08:26.480 --> 00:08:29.286
And to hear them tell the story
is they thought maybe

00:08:29.286 --> 00:08:32.880
five, maybe 10 people might be
interested in doing these

00:08:32.880 --> 00:08:35.730
things because, of course, it
will take a lot of work.

00:08:35.730 --> 00:08:36.900
You have to curate
all the speakers.

00:08:36.900 --> 00:08:40.370
You have to be really attentive
to holding an event.

00:08:40.370 --> 00:08:42.049
There's just a ton of
details to manage.

00:08:42.049 --> 00:08:45.060
So five, maybe 10.

00:08:45.060 --> 00:08:48.730
Since then, three years later,
5,000 events have happened

00:08:48.730 --> 00:08:50.060
around the world.

00:08:50.060 --> 00:08:54.960
22,000 hours of content has been
created in the process.

00:08:54.960 --> 00:08:59.940
And about 220 of those talks
have been posted on ted.com.

00:08:59.940 --> 00:09:02.200
So TED has figured out
how to create scale.

00:09:02.200 --> 00:09:05.460
Ted.com being incredibly
exclusive.

00:09:05.460 --> 00:09:07.600
Very, very small staff
of people curate

00:09:07.600 --> 00:09:08.820
what goes on ted.com.

00:09:08.820 --> 00:09:11.570
Ted conferences being semi open
in that you have to apply

00:09:11.570 --> 00:09:13.440
and be relatively
rich to get in.

00:09:13.440 --> 00:09:17.830
And then TEDx open to all people
who want to both create

00:09:17.830 --> 00:09:20.990
the event as well as people who
want to attend an event.

00:09:20.990 --> 00:09:22.430
Scale.

00:09:22.430 --> 00:09:25.000
If you tried to do that
with a budget--

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:28.320
just think about a traditional
organization like GE or I

00:09:28.320 --> 00:09:30.970
don't know, Xerox.

00:09:30.970 --> 00:09:33.180
The idea of TEDx just
kind of would--

00:09:33.180 --> 00:09:37.680
they're baffled by it because
they think we should do it.

00:09:37.680 --> 00:09:41.070
And so scale for them is much
more about we hire the people,

00:09:41.070 --> 00:09:43.490
we have the buildings,
we have the staff.

00:09:43.490 --> 00:09:45.090
So that's the gorilla
mentality.

00:09:45.090 --> 00:09:47.645
And of course, the
opposite is TEDx.

00:09:47.645 --> 00:09:48.810
It's gazelles.

00:09:48.810 --> 00:09:52.650
It's how 800 unique parties
are getting together and

00:09:52.650 --> 00:09:55.120
figuring out how to
create value.

00:09:55.120 --> 00:09:59.060
And of course, since TEDx has
started, they've had all these

00:09:59.060 --> 00:10:00.740
beautiful events all
over the earth.

00:10:00.740 --> 00:10:01.720
Brene Brown is the speaker
in the middle.

00:10:01.720 --> 00:10:04.270
And she now has 10 million views
on a talk she gave at

00:10:04.270 --> 00:10:07.030
TEDx Houston.

00:10:07.030 --> 00:10:11.380
These really flexible constructs
can apply to every

00:10:11.380 --> 00:10:13.800
part of a business.

00:10:13.800 --> 00:10:16.360
And for most traditional
organizations, they actually

00:10:16.360 --> 00:10:17.210
don't see that.

00:10:17.210 --> 00:10:19.070
So that's one of the reasons
I created this table.

00:10:19.070 --> 00:10:22.280
But in HR, the Singularity
University example shows that

00:10:22.280 --> 00:10:24.050
you don't have to have employees
creating value.

00:10:24.050 --> 00:10:27.450
In service, it used to be that
you used to have call centers.

00:10:27.450 --> 00:10:28.900
And those people worked for
you even if they were

00:10:28.900 --> 00:10:30.730
outsourced to a different
country.

00:10:30.730 --> 00:10:35.130
And McAfee mavens, or Intuit
accountants, are two examples

00:10:35.130 --> 00:10:37.080
where communities of people
actually provide

00:10:37.080 --> 00:10:38.300
peer to peer support.

00:10:38.300 --> 00:10:40.690
Intuit accountants now
answer 74% of all the

00:10:40.690 --> 00:10:42.220
questions peer to peer.

00:10:42.220 --> 00:10:45.270
And the staff has really
gotten the

00:10:45.270 --> 00:10:45.940
chance to step back.

00:10:45.940 --> 00:10:48.470
But what's more interesting,
right, is that the community

00:10:48.470 --> 00:10:52.070
of people is actually adding
value on to that platform.

00:10:52.070 --> 00:10:53.080
Capitalization.

00:10:53.080 --> 00:10:54.660
Everyone in this room has
probably heard about

00:10:54.660 --> 00:10:57.240
Kickstarter and all the various
ways in which you can

00:10:57.240 --> 00:10:58.790
fund something.

00:10:58.790 --> 00:11:00.440
But people aren't just
getting money.

00:11:00.440 --> 00:11:02.410
They're actually showing an
investment in the person.

00:11:02.410 --> 00:11:03.770
It's a community.

00:11:03.770 --> 00:11:05.990
And the way they're putting $1
into that system actually

00:11:05.990 --> 00:11:10.520
changes how committed they
are to that act.

00:11:10.520 --> 00:11:11.770
I just invested in Everpurse.

