00:13:34.190 --> 00:13:36.000
And your job was to figure out
how to give them enough money

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:38.000
so they wouldn't carry anybody
else's product.

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:40.600
And it was all this set
of monetization plays.

00:13:40.600 --> 00:13:43.690
And Evernote, as just one
example, gives away their

00:13:43.690 --> 00:13:45.350
product-- gosh, where am
I standing right now--

00:13:45.350 --> 00:13:46.690
gives away their product
knowing that

00:13:46.690 --> 00:13:48.020
enough people use them.

00:13:48.020 --> 00:13:50.510
You can monetize it in
many other ways.

00:13:50.510 --> 00:13:53.200
And then, of course, we talked
about the TED to TEDx example,

00:13:53.200 --> 00:13:56.190
which a marketing budget could
not merely do in the same way.

00:13:56.190 --> 00:13:57.120
They've created scale.

00:13:57.120 --> 00:13:58.320
And they've created
enthusiasm.

00:13:58.320 --> 00:14:00.020
And they've created
influencers.

00:14:00.020 --> 00:14:02.650
Every part of the business model
is affected when you can

00:14:02.650 --> 00:14:05.390
allow commute to actually
co-create with you.

00:14:05.390 --> 00:14:06.810
They don't work for you.

00:14:06.810 --> 00:14:08.550
You don't tell them
what to do.

00:14:08.550 --> 00:14:10.150
But this stuff happens.

00:14:10.150 --> 00:14:14.050
And in fact, when I tell this
idea to more traditional

00:14:14.050 --> 00:14:16.670
business owners, just because
I have that background, they

00:14:16.670 --> 00:14:20.375
will look at me like that's
just super scary.

00:14:20.375 --> 00:14:23.230
Is it scary for any of you?

00:14:23.230 --> 00:14:23.610
OK.

00:14:23.610 --> 00:14:24.290
Well, no.

00:14:24.290 --> 00:14:25.510
Apparently--

00:14:25.510 --> 00:14:26.576
OK, how is it scary?

00:14:26.576 --> 00:14:28.710
AUDIENCE: How do you
maintain quality?

00:14:28.710 --> 00:14:29.580
NILOFER MERCHANT: How do
you maintain quality?

00:14:29.580 --> 00:14:30.756
That's a great question.

00:14:30.756 --> 00:14:31.860
Do you have one, too?

00:14:31.860 --> 00:14:34.575
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:14:34.575 --> 00:14:37.198
where it's more like a social
mesh rather than

00:14:37.198 --> 00:14:40.300
being within the brand?

00:14:40.300 --> 00:14:42.245
NILOFER MERCHANT: Right, how
do you own the brand?

00:14:42.245 --> 00:14:43.850
That's super scary.

00:14:43.850 --> 00:14:45.800
In fact, I'm going to step away
from the slides for a

00:14:45.800 --> 00:14:47.780
second and tell you
the story of TED.

00:14:47.780 --> 00:14:53.460
So TED with its now 5,000
events, around December last

00:14:53.460 --> 00:14:57.500
year, some people in Spain
produced a TEDx.

00:14:57.500 --> 00:14:59.510
TEDx Valencia I think it was.

00:14:59.510 --> 00:15:02.250
And they had people who--

00:15:02.250 --> 00:15:04.580
I'm trying really hard not
to make fun of it--

00:15:04.580 --> 00:15:07.040
my face is going to give
it away, though.

00:15:07.040 --> 00:15:07.610
Plas--

00:15:07.610 --> 00:15:09.960
oh, god, what was the word?

00:15:09.960 --> 00:15:11.090
Plasticity.

00:15:11.090 --> 00:15:12.730
They came up with this word
that didn't mean anything.

00:15:12.730 --> 00:15:15.320
And then they had some person
who understood the psychic

00:15:15.320 --> 00:15:16.840
healing power of crystals.

00:15:16.840 --> 00:15:21.240
And they had these pretty
nonscientific people

00:15:21.240 --> 00:15:24.680
positioning all their stuff
as scientific stuff.

00:15:24.680 --> 00:15:27.480
And somebody ended up writing
a post who witnessed it and

00:15:27.480 --> 00:15:29.710
said this was an offense
on so many levels.

00:15:29.710 --> 00:15:31.120
Like it was an offense
to science.

00:15:31.120 --> 00:15:33.100
It was an offense to the people
who had to witness it.

00:15:33.100 --> 00:15:34.060
It was an offense to TED.

00:15:34.060 --> 00:15:36.010
It was just an offense to-- oh,
and I think the last line

00:15:36.010 --> 00:15:37.980
was, and to common sense
because it was just--

00:15:37.980 --> 00:15:40.180
it was ridiculous.

00:15:40.180 --> 00:15:44.410
So here many, many miles away
happening in a different

00:15:44.410 --> 00:15:49.750
language and somebody on
Reddit ends up posting,

00:15:49.750 --> 00:15:52.340
originally in the Spanish
thing, and posting it on

00:15:52.340 --> 00:15:57.320
Reddit saying, TEDs name is
being dragged through the mud.

00:15:57.320 --> 00:15:59.860
5,000 people comment on it.

00:15:59.860 --> 00:16:02.860
Within 24 hours, it goes all
over Twitter and all the

00:16:02.860 --> 00:16:05.160
logical places.

00:16:05.160 --> 00:16:07.320
And TED starts stepping
into the fray.

00:16:07.320 --> 00:16:10.710
And first they say, people
are allowed to

00:16:10.710 --> 00:16:12.800
have their own stuff.

00:16:12.800 --> 00:16:13.750
And that sometimes happens.

00:16:13.750 --> 00:16:16.040
We'll manage it later
and yada yada.

00:16:16.040 --> 00:16:19.070
And then what happens in this
dialogue, though, because it's

00:16:19.070 --> 00:16:21.820
not just a one way thing is
they use it to learn.

00:16:21.820 --> 00:16:23.120
And somebody says,
you know what?

00:16:23.120 --> 00:16:26.350
You're not giving your people
enough guidance as to how to

00:16:26.350 --> 00:16:27.850
pick speakers.

00:16:27.850 --> 00:16:30.320
And so a bunch of your content
is pseudoscience crap.

00:16:30.320 --> 00:16:32.100
In fact, there's one
that's beautiful.

00:16:32.100 --> 00:16:34.580
If you go on Quora, and
there's somebody who's

00:16:34.580 --> 00:16:37.290
actually posted a TED talk and
says, how long can you get

00:16:37.290 --> 00:16:39.150
through this talk without
wanting to throw up?

00:16:39.150 --> 00:16:43.230
And it's a physicist over at
Stanford that says not long

00:16:43.230 --> 00:16:45.370
and just debunks the talk.

00:16:45.370 --> 00:16:49.140
That talk has since
been removed.

00:16:49.140 --> 00:16:52.750
The thing that TED had to do was
to step into the dialogue

00:16:52.750 --> 00:16:54.970
and figure out what is
it they could learn.

00:16:54.970 --> 00:16:57.070
And then, they actually ended
up posting a multi-page kind

00:16:57.070 --> 00:16:57.480
of process.

00:16:57.480 --> 00:16:59.890
Like people, we gotta
fix this.

00:16:59.890 --> 00:17:01.740
And this is not our
problem, TED.

00:17:01.740 --> 00:17:05.180
This is our problem, TED.

00:17:05.180 --> 00:17:06.785
And they actually asked
the community to

00:17:06.785 --> 00:17:08.010
step into the framework.

00:17:08.010 --> 00:17:09.910
Like step up how much
you're curating.

00:17:09.910 --> 00:17:11.640
Step up how you're doing it.

00:17:11.640 --> 00:17:14.950
And so, certainly, there's a
risk in all of that stuff

00:17:14.950 --> 00:17:15.819
that's happened.

00:17:15.819 --> 00:17:20.589
But what they actually said
is openness wins overall.

00:17:20.589 --> 00:17:22.990
As much as we make these people
part of our co-creative

00:17:22.990 --> 00:17:25.280
process, they are also
part of the solution.

00:17:25.280 --> 00:17:26.710
So in the problem
is a solution.

00:17:26.710 --> 00:17:29.030
And they ended up posting a
whole series of things and

00:17:29.030 --> 00:17:30.830
working through that.

00:17:30.830 --> 00:17:32.930
And I think it's just terrifying
for anyone who owns

00:17:32.930 --> 00:17:35.900
a brand because your brand can
be drug through the mud.

00:17:35.900 --> 00:17:38.970
And of course, there's a whole
control issue about how do you

00:17:38.970 --> 00:17:40.100
manage quality.

00:17:40.100 --> 00:17:42.780
And in TED's case, one of the
ways they manage quality is to

00:17:42.780 --> 00:17:44.500
say, this section
of it is free.

00:17:44.500 --> 00:17:46.440
1,000 flowers bloom.

00:17:46.440 --> 00:17:49.980
And this section we highly
curate, TED.com.

00:17:49.980 --> 00:17:51.660
And so how do you allow--

00:17:51.660 --> 00:17:53.570
because the brand is so
indistinct to some people.

00:17:53.570 --> 00:17:55.690
How do you do both and
make sure you're

00:17:55.690 --> 00:17:57.190
managing your quality?

00:17:57.190 --> 00:17:59.715
So I hope I answered both
those two concerns.

00:17:59.715 --> 00:18:01.860
But I think it's scary on
multiple levels than just the

00:18:01.860 --> 00:18:04.350
ones that you've mentioned.

00:18:04.350 --> 00:18:09.430
It's when you're leading
a leaderless context,

00:18:09.430 --> 00:18:10.680
how do you do that?

00:18:12.910 --> 00:18:16.230
And if you went to business
school like I did, the way

00:18:16.230 --> 00:18:18.730
we're taught leadership
is you're in charge.

00:18:18.730 --> 00:18:22.080
And it's about how much you're
leading people or resources.

00:18:22.080 --> 00:18:25.850
And power comes from leading
people or resources, not about

00:18:25.850 --> 00:18:27.690
whether or not you're
leading an idea.

00:18:27.690 --> 00:18:29.880
And that's the fundamental shift
here that we're talking

00:18:29.880 --> 00:18:35.210
about is TED's leading an idea
and so are a whole bunch of

00:18:35.210 --> 00:18:35.830
other organizations.

00:18:35.830 --> 00:18:36.820
There's a question.

00:18:36.820 --> 00:18:38.120
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:18:38.120 --> 00:18:39.756
TED is obviously a
great example.

00:18:39.756 --> 00:18:44.208
But the reason why people want
to help TED is because TED is

00:18:44.208 --> 00:18:44.994
a very strong brand.

00:18:44.994 --> 00:18:45.485
NILOFER MERCHANT: Yes.

00:18:45.485 --> 00:18:46.960
As [INAUDIBLE].

00:18:46.960 --> 00:18:50.228
AUDIENCE: However, if I'm
starting TED, I don't think I

00:18:50.228 --> 00:18:52.190
would get the same following.

00:18:52.190 --> 00:18:57.100
It really has to do, once you're
already a success,

00:18:57.100 --> 00:19:00.384
people wouldn't [INAUDIBLE] time
into helping [INAUDIBLE].

00:19:00.384 --> 00:19:03.310
Also because in their own self
interest that they want to

00:19:03.310 --> 00:19:04.340
become part of that success.

00:19:04.340 --> 00:19:05.850
NILOFER MERCHANT: So you're
raising a really good point,

00:19:05.850 --> 00:19:07.980
which is how do you get people
to run with you.

00:19:07.980 --> 00:19:11.260
And so in TED's case, they had
enough of a magnetic pull.

00:19:11.260 --> 00:19:13.790
But in other cases, it's
figuring out how do you have

00:19:13.790 --> 00:19:15.490
shared interests.

00:19:15.490 --> 00:19:17.920
So in TED's case, they're
actually doing this thing

00:19:17.920 --> 00:19:21.800
where people who want to bring
ideas to market use the master

00:19:21.800 --> 00:19:24.310
brand of TED and are able to
invest literally hundreds of

00:19:24.310 --> 00:19:25.570
hours in order to do that.

00:19:25.570 --> 00:19:28.070
The question is why are all
those people doing it?

00:19:28.070 --> 00:19:30.500
And how do you really
tap into that?

00:19:30.500 --> 00:19:32.030
Kickstarter has started--

00:19:32.030 --> 00:19:33.200
it's only three years old.

00:19:33.200 --> 00:19:34.500
It's kind of hard to imagine
that because it's had such a

00:19:34.500 --> 00:19:35.510
profound effect.

00:19:35.510 --> 00:19:38.760
But what it's tapping into is
this desire that's beyond

00:19:38.760 --> 00:19:41.440
money, about how can I commit
to certain things?

00:19:41.440 --> 00:19:43.500
And what is this shared product
I might want to bring

00:19:43.500 --> 00:19:45.700
into this market or this shared
purpose I might have

00:19:45.700 --> 00:19:46.970
with someone?

00:19:46.970 --> 00:19:49.050
And that starts to create
the magnet.

00:19:49.050 --> 00:19:51.200
And so instead of thinking
about how do I tell other

00:19:51.200 --> 00:19:54.640
people, it's what's that
magnetic force of purpose?

00:19:54.640 --> 00:19:59.950
And how do I get it to be so
darn strong that they'll come?

00:19:59.950 --> 00:20:01.740
And once you tap into that,
you start tapping into a

00:20:01.740 --> 00:20:04.030
different source, a
creative source.

00:20:04.030 --> 00:20:05.530
It causes people to run
with you using the

00:20:05.530 --> 00:20:07.570
visual behind me.

00:20:07.570 --> 00:20:11.100
And that's what I'm trying to
talk to you is the shift used

00:20:11.100 --> 00:20:12.780
to be that you used
to do stuff by

00:20:12.780 --> 00:20:16.400
yourself, alone, apart.

00:20:16.400 --> 00:20:20.870
And power came from the value
chain kind of process of being

00:20:20.870 --> 00:20:22.260
distinctly apart.

00:20:22.260 --> 00:20:25.020
And then the other one is about
community, which is how

00:20:25.020 --> 00:20:27.880
do I get a bunch of people
to start working in

00:20:27.880 --> 00:20:29.130
collaboration?

00:20:29.130 --> 00:20:31.450
And that shifts scale.

00:20:31.450 --> 00:20:34.380
But it also means that from a
marketing perspective, you're

00:20:34.380 --> 00:20:35.660
no longer just talking
about a product.

00:20:35.660 --> 00:20:37.180
So just take 20 years ago.

00:20:37.180 --> 00:20:38.690
We take it for granted today.

00:20:38.690 --> 00:20:41.310
But 20 years ago, the power of
being able to sell a product

00:20:41.310 --> 00:20:43.640
was how big a megaphone
you could have.

00:20:43.640 --> 00:20:46.240
And that share of voice, as it
was called in the marketplace,

00:20:46.240 --> 00:20:48.750
allowed you to dominate how much
you could then exclude

00:20:48.750 --> 00:20:50.290
other people.

00:20:50.290 --> 00:20:51.450
That's not really--

00:20:51.450 --> 00:20:52.660
not the case anymore.

00:20:52.660 --> 00:20:56.350
So what causes people to then be
pulled into the story with

00:20:56.350 --> 00:20:59.500
you is about purpose
and who can join

00:20:59.500 --> 00:21:01.950
with you in that endeavor.

00:21:01.950 --> 00:21:04.130
In the TED example, it's really
easy to see the shared

00:21:04.130 --> 00:21:07.330
purpose is you get to create
content and ideas that matter.

00:21:07.330 --> 00:21:08.750
But what is the shared
purpose--

00:21:08.750 --> 00:21:10.380
let's take Google+.

00:21:10.380 --> 00:21:13.250
Why does someone invest
in Google+

00:21:13.250 --> 00:21:16.210
versus, let's say, Facebook?

00:21:16.210 --> 00:21:18.310
