And he should be thinking
about how do I act more

00:25:07.130 --> 00:25:10.190
gazelle like because the
architecture that they've been

00:25:10.190 --> 00:25:11.870
using is I make a
lot of stuff.

00:25:11.870 --> 00:25:12.940
And I sell a lot of it.

00:25:12.940 --> 00:25:14.770
And that's how I get
to have scale.

00:25:14.770 --> 00:25:16.490
That's how I become
successful.

00:25:16.490 --> 00:25:20.280
That is an architecture of 1970
of a company Purina dog

00:25:20.280 --> 00:25:21.850
chow might include.

00:25:21.850 --> 00:25:23.355
Sorry, that's a personal
reference he said to

00:25:23.355 --> 00:25:24.750
me a long time ago.

00:25:24.750 --> 00:25:28.280
And those gorilla constructs
are no longer valid.

00:25:28.280 --> 00:25:30.530
But that is largely the
constructs that are taught in

00:25:30.530 --> 00:25:32.390
business school today.

00:25:32.390 --> 00:25:36.160
And they are essentially
eliminating or not seeing this

00:25:36.160 --> 00:25:36.920
other set of apertures.

00:25:36.920 --> 00:25:39.350
So I just want to expand the
framework of how we might

00:25:39.350 --> 00:25:41.620
think about business models
in the future.

00:25:41.620 --> 00:25:44.460
The first is thinking about
scale not as an axis about

00:25:44.460 --> 00:25:47.510
just the stuff I do alone and
separate but the stuff I do

00:25:47.510 --> 00:25:49.680
with others.

00:25:49.680 --> 00:25:51.970
That is so fundamental
a tectonic shift.

00:25:51.970 --> 00:25:53.940
And this group might take
it for granted.

00:25:53.940 --> 00:25:55.060
But the broader world
does not.

00:25:55.060 --> 00:25:57.420
And business models don't
play to that.

00:25:57.420 --> 00:25:59.230
And the second is to think
about not just what we

00:25:59.230 --> 00:26:02.290
produce, but what is the way
in which we engage other

00:26:02.290 --> 00:26:04.140
people in that purpose because
that changes things.

