So my opening line of my "Havard
Magazine" article is

00:45:11.760 --> 00:45:15.360
what fucking bullshit because
I'm quoting the professor

00:45:15.360 --> 00:45:16.910
who's like commenting
on the talk.

00:45:16.910 --> 00:45:18.610
So I feel pretty good that I
managed to start a "Havard

00:45:18.610 --> 00:45:21.620
Magazine" article with what
fucking bullshit.

00:45:21.620 --> 00:45:25.070
Try sneaking that in.

00:45:25.070 --> 00:45:26.870
But what that ends up
becoming is peer

00:45:26.870 --> 00:45:27.920
review raises an issue.

00:45:27.920 --> 00:45:29.116
And then of course, there's
a judgment call.

00:45:29.116 --> 00:45:33.410
So it never eliminates the role
of the central body if

00:45:33.410 --> 00:45:34.650
you still want to manage that.

00:45:34.650 --> 00:45:37.290
But you get like 99% of
it to happen out here.

00:45:37.290 --> 00:45:40.490
And you want accountability
because this is

00:45:40.490 --> 00:45:41.520
all about an exchange.

00:45:41.520 --> 00:45:45.240
So you can't sort of hold onto
the accountability and expect

00:45:45.240 --> 00:45:47.190
people to feel ownership.

00:45:47.190 --> 00:45:48.680
It works inside an
organization.

00:45:48.680 --> 00:45:49.890
It works external.

00:45:49.890 --> 00:45:52.470
The more you give people power,
the more they end up

00:45:52.470 --> 00:45:55.210
creating and bring their
full selves to work.

00:45:55.210 --> 00:45:56.650
So you want everything
like that.

00:45:56.650 --> 00:45:58.760
You want to figure out how do I
assign this thing that might

00:45:58.760 --> 00:46:02.130
be in my head as far away from
me as possible so the thing

00:46:02.130 --> 00:46:03.980
that really matters is managed,
and everything else

00:46:03.980 --> 00:46:05.770
can be their own source
of creativity.

